Observation Details: As decribed, the bird was seen actively flying behind and around the vessel. As the bird was seen the following day, we assume that the bird had been ships-assisted during the night. A search on the ship was done on both days with a negative result. Since the bird was seen souht of 60 degrees south it may count as the first observation of this species in Antarctica, when accounting 60 degrees as the limit for Antarctica. I have banded barn owls in Denmark, and hence recognized  the bird as this species. Recognizing its very widely distributed and occurs in a large number of  subspecies, it fits well with the description of the subsp. tuidara.  Since an unidentified white-rumped swallow was seen flying around the vessel initially, together with the owl, I got the impression, that some atmospheric conditions that had favoured birds spring migration had occured, and for some reason, these two birds had overshot their migratory goal and ended up at sea, being attracked by the presence of the vessel.

I was witness to, along with several others, the re-release of five juvenile barn owls back into Sahara Woods on this date. The five had been hatchlings and were being raised in the owl box near the Sahara Woods office earlier in the year. A predator, probably a great horned owl, killed the mother. IDNR workers rescued the young barn owls from the box and got them to wildlife rehab expert Beverly Shofstall of Carterville. They all survived, and Beverly released them on this date. They all immediately flew into various parts of the available woods.

Observation Details: Fledgling Barn Owl found unmoving in the road as cars drove past on each side of it. I stood guard so it wouldn't be hit by cars but it still didn't move after several minutes. I held up a blanket to screen out the view of traffic and passersby, and after getting a little privacy, it walked over to nearby shrubbery unaided, though still plainly visible. I continued to observe from a distance and ensured it wasn't harassed by the pedestrians until it eventually made its way to denser cover and rested. Update: Cathy Strickland checked on the owl the morning of 4/28 and found it had been run over by a car.

It dropped down into the base of the hills where it stayed despite a Raven taking a few swoops at it, and a Red-tailed circled above it once or twice.  Was still there when I returned two hours later.

Media notes: photo by Jon Dunn.  Words cannot describe the excitement of seeing the first Barn Owl that has been documented in the Saginaw Bay area since the last sighting at Shiawassee NWR in July of 1978. At 8:15 A.M. my friends and I first observed the bird in flight ... an unusually slow wing beat with wings stretching far forward, the tips twisting and cupping to form a scoop to collect precious air. The flight was so slow that I expected the bird to suddenly drop vertically and belly flop to the ground. It flew directly over Lynda Camburn and she excitely identified it as a Barn Owl! Later in the afternoon the owl took roost in a stand of pine trees, allowing us to admire and study it. That is where Jon Dunn took this photo. This Barn Owl was the 301st bird species to be documented at Tawas Point State Park.

Media notes: This is the view when peering inside the nest box via a one inch crack under the unlatched top. The five owlets were about one to two feet away from me. They had not yet left the nest.
Observation Details: 1 adult, 5 owlets. The adult, presumably the mother, was perched near the rafters in the barn. The owlets were in their wooden nest box. Our trip leader told us that he expects them to fledge in about two weeks. At one point a young Amish boy raised the nest box lid and the owlets could be heard hissing and clacking. The image of these beautiful owlets all huddled together, looking back at me with their large black eyes from only a couple foot away, will stay with me the rest of my life! Some pictures are better than none, but they fail to capture the magical experience.

I have no idea of what this owl was doing.   I saw it about 10:00 in the sun, on a low branch with wings  hanging down. The owl did move it's head and neck up and down as well as back and forth several times, maybe had a back problem. Two RTHA on tree limbs above.  I looked at them a few minutes and saw no interaction between the birds.  I got pictures from two very different angles; light and color very different on each angle.

Caught our eye sitting on fence post as we drove along road at sunset.  Stopped for photo.  It was perched facing away from us for about a minute then turned to check us out before flying into Sabal Palm.  We drove by again 10 minutes later and found it near its original perch, this time trying to wrangle some prey out of the tall grasses.  Gorgeous feathers in the setting sun.  There are theories that this species is bioluminescent.

Observation Details: Dos individuos anidaban sobre el tronco de una palma a los 1450 msnm en un condominio de la Vereda San Peregrino de Manizales; al parecer uno de ellos era un subadulto.  Vocalizaciones constantes e intensas.  Se mostraron muy tranquilos con la presencia de humanos y perros.  Pocos registros en Manizales y el departamento de Caldas confirmados en eBird; algunos ejemplares de museo habían sido útiles para su confirmación, sin embargo recientemente varios individuos han sido observados comúnmente en el departamento.  Al parecer se trata de una Hembra adulta con un subadulto, teniendo en cuenta que usualmente la hembra es quien cuida de los polluelos,  uno parecía serlo por su tamaño (Izq)  También podría tratarse de una pareja, pero la actitud sumisa del individuo de la izquierda nos permitió inferir que quizá podrían ser madre e hijo.

Heard the kestrels making a racket about something and saw some kind of large raptor fly from a large maple close to me to a further away tree. Thought something seemed different about the way it flew and the form of it compared to the hawks I usually see, so walked over to get a closer look and it flew from that tree into a pine tree across the road. This time I was sure it was an owl. I was thinking it was either a long eared owl or a short eared owl. Got my backpack with my camera and binoculars and relocated the owl and saw it was a Barn Owl. First time seeing one in the wild. Very unexpected yard bird!

Able to observe it triangulating with head and body!, head turning to view the darker outlined 'heart' of its facial disc, able to enjoy its lovely caramel coloration when the sun hit its flanks, a darker gray/caramel on back, spotted 'embellishments'; no vocals. All very respectful of its space...........hope that continues. Unfortunately the word of its presence leaked out quickly today but wished to wait some days before listing

Nest boxes are maintained periodically (about once every 5 years) during the fall/winter season when nests are less likely to be active, in order to reduce disturbance to these state-endangered birds.  Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. You can help barn owls by donating to the Nongame Wildlife Fund, or by building and installing a nest box in open grassland habitat. Learn more: https://www.in.gov/dnr/fish-and-wildlife/wildlife-resources/animals/barn-owl/

One hunting just after the sun went down behind the mountains. Harriers were still out. Must have been one hungry bird. It really put on a show for at least 30 min, allowing me to study the Barn Owl body shape and flight + foraging style. Graceful fliers, with a steady wing beat cadence of about 2-3 beats per second and usually fairly deep wing beats, wings held bowed downwards, flying within 5-10 feet off the ground and occasionally twice that height.  Half an hour after sunset, there were at least 3, and maybe 5, Barn Owls hunting.  One bird flew only 10-20 feet above my head, clearly curious: it banked, circled me, and moved on.  One bird called: "hiyaaaaa"

Facial ruff darker buff than male and with black-tipped feathers extending farther up on the sides of the ruff than in males. Facial disk white but heavily tinged with vinaceous brown. Throat, breast, belly, and legs buff heavily marked with spots usually larger than those of males." "Under parts variable with females tending to have more and larger spotting on wings and breast than males."

Observation Details: Thanks to Carl and Catherine Miller for discovering this barn owl, photographing it, and posting it yesterday in their Dobbins Farm eBird listing.  This morning, following the excellent directions provided by the Millers, I went to the tree on the corner of Fred Dobbins Road and Fork School Road.  About two-thirds of the way up the tree, there is a large cavity on the road side of the tree, and although  the light and weather conditions were poor, I was able to see the barn owl in the back of the cavity.  This barn owl is distinguished by its white heart-shaped face and lack of ear tufts, and it iclearly appears to be the same owl observed and photographed by the Millers yesterday.  I am listing this bird as part of my Fork School list because my practice has been to use the Fork School hotspot for all sightings east of Fork School road.

Observation Details: This nesting site was first discovered in 2020. No offspring were confirmed in 2020-2022 although the landowner noted a pair of birds. I have been advised not to disclose the location and visit the site only once per year to avoid disturbing the birds.  I hope they continue successful breeding and increase the Barn Owl population in our area!

Observation Details: First observed at 6:51AM, perched on a small pole, along the berm. The bird flew across the road and was coursing the boulder field. A short while later, it was perched on a wire along the road getting dive-bombed by a Peregrine. When the owl had a chance to escape, it flew down low out of sight, by the mounds at the southeast end of the field. Ten minutes after this, the bird was coursing again. I walked over to the field, only to find it getting dive-bombed by the PEFA again, as it perched on a wire in the north(central) part of the field! When the falcon gave up, the Barn continued coursing even though the sun was rising. I last saw the bird at 7:26AM perched on a telephone pole along the berm, before it flew off. Interestingly, all the gulls and Brant flushed in the cove (misidentification on their part). In my experience, Barn Owls will hunt past sunrise in the winter months, especially when food stressed.

First observed at 6:51AM, perched on a small pole, along the berm. The bird flew across the road and was coursing the boulder field. A short while later, it was perched on a wire along the road getting dive-bombed by a Peregrine. When the owl had a chance to escape, it flew down low out of sight, by the mounds at the southeast end of the field. Ten minutes after this, the bird was coursing again. I walked over to the field, only to find it getting dive-bombed by the PEFA again, as it perched on a wire in the north(central) part of the field! When the falcon gave up, the Barn continued coursing even though the sun was rising. I last saw the bird at 7:26AM perched on a telephone pole along the berm, before it flew off. Interestingly, all the gulls and Brant flushed in the cove (misidentification on their part). In my experience, Barn Owls will hunt past sunrise in the winter months, especially when food stressed.

This is the same site where I saw a Barn Owl in October 2020.  The land owner has not seen the owl in the last couple of years.  It is a possible nesting site, so is only listed by county. I only saw one bird, though.  In 2020 the owner saw 2 at one point, but not any young.

One hunting just after the sun went down behind the mountains. Harriers were still out. Must have been one hungry bird. It really put on a show for at least 30 min, allowing me to study the Barn Owl body shape and flight + foraging style. Graceful fliers, with a steady wing beat cadence of about 2-3 beats per second and usually fairly deep wing beats, wings held bowed downwards, flying within 5-10 feet off the ground and occasionally twice that height.  Half an hour after sunset, there were at least 3, and maybe 5, Barn Owls hunting.  One bird flew only 10-20 feet above my head, clearly curious: it banked, circled me, and moved on.  One bird called: "hiyaaaaa"

I couldn't make a clear ID and he allowed me to look in his barn.  Above the dark hay mow was a cupula which was even more dark.  It seemed like the perfect place for a Barn Owl.  The first picture is of the Barn Owl perched in the cupula.  To my distress, my presence there flushed the owl despite my best efforts. I guess it is unlikely a creature that can hear a mouse's heartbeat under six inches of snow would be unaware of an intruder in its roost.   I heard Blue Jays scolding outside and found the owl in dense trees for the subsequent pictures.  I then left without disturbing it further.  The landowner said he had seen two "white owls" there in mid September.  He has never seen any young.  This post is delayed as I was researching the appropriate response to this siting.  I registered the siting with Anna Buckardt, the Avian ecologist for the Iowa DNR.  She told me the location would be kept under wraps at the DNR and used for monitoring Barn Owl populations.  She is aware of only about 13 nesting sites in Iowa.  It is my understanding that locations of nesting sites should be reported as county only.  I will look forward to asking the landowner next year if they came back and hopefully produced offspring.

An amazing experience! We arrived at the barn owl box just before sunset and decided to park and wait in our vehicle. Having never seen a barn owl before, we were excited at the possibility of glimpsing one. Just after sunset, we were rewarded with two barn owl faces showing in the window.   About ten or fifteen minutes later, one of the barn owls perched in the window and took flight to a nearby tree. The second owl popped up into the window, with a third showing its face! The second owl then flew from the box and joined the first in the tree. To our surprise, after the second owl left, a fourth one popped into view! The third owl (we believe to be a fledgling) poked its head out the window and seemed to be looking around and calculating how to join its parents. It was bobbing and circling its head repeatedly. After a couple of minutes of that, the third owl perched in the window and took a sort of clumsy flight to the same tree as the first two.   After it left, a fifth owl face came into view! The fourth and fifth owls spent the next several minutes looking out of the box, seemingly trying to figure out how to join their parents and sibling. After a lot of head circling, the fourth owl perched in the window, but was much less confident than the third. At one point, it seemed to lose its balance and nearly fell from the box! It held on with talons and used its wings to prevent the fall, then retreated into the box. A moment later it was back perching, and after more calculating, it launched and took a downward arc toward the trees (we cheered inside the car).  Light was fading quickly by now, but we hoped to see the fifth one fly as well. Despite perching in the window multiple times, it retreated back to the box every time. Several times it stood sideways in the window and stuck one wing out and flapped. We ended up leaving before it left the box, simply because we could barely see it anymore. As the last one was contemplating leaving, on of the parents went on top of the box seemingly trying to encourage it. That parent then flew to a tree near us and began screaming, which we had never heard before. Overall an awesome experience!   We are presuming that the five owls in the box are a family, with the first two the parents. They were quick to leave the box, waited in the trees, flew around to several trees nearby, and also landed on top of the corn crib and the nest box. They also showed good flying ability. We then figured the last three were their young who were hesitant leaving the box and seemed clumsy in their flight. I read that young barn owls may return to their nest box to roost even after their first flight. Based on the behavior we saw, we're wondering if this was close to their first flight (if not the first, after seeing the fifth owl so unsure of flying).  Hopefully the last owl joined them later in the night!

Dos individuos anidaban sobre el tronco de una palma a los 1450 msnm en un condominio de la Vereda San Peregrino de Manizales; al parecer uno de ellos era un subadulto.  Vocalizaciones constantes e intensas.  Se mostraron muy tranquilos con la presencia de humanos y perros.  Pocos registros en Manizales y el departamento de Caldas confirmados en eBird; algunos ejemplares de museo habían sido útiles para su confirmación, sin embargo recientemente varios individuos han sido observados comúnmente en el departamento.  Al parecer se trata de una Hembra adulta con un subadulto, teniendo en cuenta que usualmente la hembra es quien cuida de los polluelos,  uno parecía serlo por su tamaño (Izq)  También podría tratarse de una pareja, pero la actitud sumisa del individuo de la izquierda nos permitió inferir que quizá podrían ser madre e hijo.

Adult female in DNR nest box. Five cold abandoned eggs which should have been big chicks on this date. It’s possible that the eggs were abandoned during the extreme cold weather we had in late December (below zero and windy for multiple days)  Encountered while performing necessary nest box maintenance (cleaning out and making small repairs when needed). Nest boxes are maintained periodically (about once every 5 years) during the fall/winter season when nests are less likely to be active, in order to reduce disturbance to these state-endangered birds.  Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. You can help barn owls by donating to the Nongame Wildlife Fund, or by building and installing a nest box in open grassland habitat. Learn more: https://www.in.gov/dnr/fish-and-wildlife/wildlife-resources/animals/barn-owl/

An amazing experience! We arrived at the barn owl box just before sunset and decided to park and wait in our vehicle. Having never seen a barn owl before, we were excited at the possibility of glimpsing one. Just after sunset, we were rewarded with two barn owl faces showing in the window.   About ten or fifteen minutes later, one of the barn owls perched in the window and took flight to a nearby tree. The second owl popped up into the window, with a third showing its face! The second owl then flew from the box and joined the first in the tree. To our surprise, after the second owl left, a fourth one popped into view! The third owl (we believe to be a fledgling) poked its head out the window and seemed to be looking around and calculating how to join its parents. It was bobbing and circling its head repeatedly. After a couple of minutes of that, the third owl perched in the window and took a sort of clumsy flight to the same tree as the first two.   After it left, a fifth owl face came into view! The fourth and fifth owls spent the next several minutes looking out of the box, seemingly trying to figure out how to join their parents and sibling. After a lot of head circling, the fourth owl perched in the window, but was much less confident than the third. At one point, it seemed to lose its balance and nearly fell from the box! It held on with talons and used its wings to prevent the fall, then retreated into the box. A moment later it was back perching, and after more calculating, it launched and took a downward arc toward the trees (we cheered inside the car).  Light was fading quickly by now, but we hoped to see the fifth one fly as well. Despite perching in the window multiple times, it retreated back to the box every time. Several times it stood sideways in the window and stuck one wing out and flapped. We ended up leaving before it left the box, simply because we could barely see it anymore. As the last one was contemplating leaving, on of the parents went on top of the box seemingly trying to encourage it. That parent then flew to a tree near us and began screaming, which we had never heard before. Overall an awesome experience!   We are presuming that the five owls in the box are a family, with the first two the parents. They were quick to leave the box, waited in the trees, flew around to several trees nearby, and also landed on top of the corn crib and the nest box. They also showed good flying ability. We then figured the last three were their young who were hesitant leaving the box and seemed clumsy in their flight. I read that young barn owls may return to their nest box to roost even after their first flight. Based on the behavior we saw, we're wondering if this was close to their first flight (if not the first, after seeing the fifth owl so unsure of flying).  Hopefully the last owl joined them later in the night!

Able to observe it triangulating with head and body!, head turning to view the darker outlined 'heart' of its facial disc, able to enjoy its lovely caramel coloration when the sun hit its flanks, a darker gray/caramel on back, spotted 'embellishments'; no vocals. Encountered while performing necessary nest box maintenance (cleaning out and making small repairs when needed). Nest boxes are maintained periodically (about once every 5 years) during the fall/winter season when nests are less likely to be active, in order to reduce disturbance to these state-endangered birds.  Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. You can help barn owls by donating to the Nongame Wildlife Fund, or by building and installing a nest box in open grassland habitat. Learn more: https://www.in.gov/dnr/fish-and-wildlife/wildlife-resources/animals/barn-owl/

An amazing experience! We arrived at the barn owl box just before sunset and decided to park and wait in our vehicle. Having never seen a barn owl before, we were excited at the possibility of glimpsing one. Just after sunset, we were rewarded with two barn owl faces showing in the window.   About ten or fifteen minutes later, one of the barn owls perched in the window and took flight to a nearby tree. The second owl popped up into the window, with a third showing its face! The second owl then flew from the box and joined the first in the tree. To our surprise, after the second owl left, a fourth one popped into view! The third owl (we believe to be a fledgling) poked its head out the window and seemed to be looking around and calculating how to join its parents. It was bobbing and circling its head repeatedly. After a couple of minutes of that, the third owl perched in the window and took a sort of clumsy flight to the same tree as the first two.   After it left, a fifth owl face came into view! The fourth and fifth owls spent the next several minutes looking out of the box, seemingly trying to figure out how to join their parents and sibling. After a lot of head circling, the fourth owl perched in the window, but was much less confident than the third. At one point, it seemed to lose its balance and nearly fell from the box! It held on with talons and used its wings to prevent the fall, then retreated into the box. A moment later it was back perching, and after more calculating, it launched and took a downward arc toward the trees (we cheered inside the car).  Light was fading quickly by now, but we hoped to see the fifth one fly as well. Despite perching in the window multiple times, it retreated back to the box every time. Several times it stood sideways in the window and stuck one wing out and flapped. We ended up leaving before it left the box, simply because we could barely see it anymore. As the last one was contemplating leaving, on of the parents went on top of the box seemingly trying to encourage it. That parent then flew to a tree near us and began screaming, which we had never heard before. Overall an awesome experience!   We are presuming that the five owls in the box are a family, with the first two the parents. They were quick to leave the box, waited in the trees, flew around to several trees nearby, and also landed on top of the corn crib and the nest box. They also showed good flying ability. We then figured the last three were their young who were hesitant leaving the box and seemed clumsy in their flight. I read that young barn owls may return to their nest box to roost even after their first flight. Based on the behavior we saw, we're wondering if this was close to their first flight (if not the first, after seeing the fifth owl so unsure of flying).  Hopefully the last owl joined them later in the night!

One hunting just after the sun went down behind the mountains. Harriers were still out. Must have been one hungry bird. It really put on a show for at least 30 min, allowing me to study the Barn Owl body shape and flight + foraging style. Graceful fliers, with a steady wing beat cadence of about 2-3 beats per second and usually fairly deep wing beats, wings held bowed downwards, flying within 5-10 feet off the ground and occasionally twice that height.  Half an hour after sunset, there were at least 3, and maybe 5, Barn Owls hunting.  One bird flew only 10-20 feet above my head, clearly curious: it banked, circled me, and moved on.  One bird called: "hiyaaaaa"

This is private property, but owner Adriano welcomes visitors to his farmstand, featuring his own chocolate, shade-grown coffee, and moonshine.  When our Overseas Adventure Travel group first arrived, there was no one home -- just the radio playing to a very friendly half-grown puppy, while the farmstand table displayed its wares on the honor system.  As our guide was showing us around, though, the proprietor returned from his errand.  Practically the first words out of his mouth were, "I have an owl for you!"  (While this wasn't a birding tour, he may have noticed my binos; and anyway, everybody loves owls.)  Impossibly tiny -- the size of a screech owl.

Media notes: Field sketch in pen.
Observation Details: I know I surprised this owl but I think I was more surprised when I realized what it was. Spooked from about 5 meters up in willow tree along pond.   What I noticed first was how white the bird was. It looked like a huge moth with its very broad wings. It had a big head with a very conspicuous dark-edged facial disc. The top of head was flat with no ear tufts. The body tapered down to a short tail.   Size appeared to be slightly bigger than a crow But with much broader wings.  It did not call. It flew fairly low with direct flight disappearing behind some trees.   This is new state bird for me. I am very familiar with bird from when I lived in California and Arizona. The last time I saw was in Grand Cayman 5 years ago.  I did a quick sketch after seeing it, jotting down notes, uploaded here.

Observation Details: After recent report by Pam Overmyer (thank you!), hoped it would show again.  While waiting for it to get a bit darker, my wife, Cyndi, walked shoreline along Lighthouse Pond for Nelson's Sparrows; none of those, but flushed Barn Owl out of palmetto. It flew north out of her sight over Lighthouse Pond.  Relocated several minutes later flying over the salt marsh east of Lighthouse Road.  Over the next 30-40 minutes watched it fly over salt marsh and make a couple of round trips around Lighthouse Pond, flying by twice within 10-15 feet.

One adult and four older nestlings/fledglings at 2 different DNR barn owl nest box sites. All were seen while performing necessary nest box maintenance (cleaning out and making small repairs to the box when needed). The amount of fresh pellet mass inside the box that had the adult roosting inside the box indicated that there was a nest in the box in 2017. The box with at least four older chicks was not disturbed. These chicks were right on the verge of fledging or had recently fledged and were still roosting inside the box. Small tufts of down were visible in the breasts if these owls. Since this is a dangerous time in the lives of naive young barn owls, we did not want to flush them from their nest box. Another visit will be made in a couple months after chicks have dispersed and the box will be cleaned out then. Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. You can help barn owls by donating to the Nongame Fund, or by building and installing a nest box in open grassland habitat. Learn more: http://www.in.gov/dnr/fishwild/3382.htm

Observation Details: Not this exact location. Female incubating one egg inside a DNR nest box. Encountered while performing necessary nest box maintenance (cleaning out and making small repairs when needed). Nest boxes are maintained periodically (about once every 5 years) during the fall/winter season when nests are less likely to be active, in order to reduce disturbance to these state-endangered birds.  Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. One hunting just after the sun went down behind the mountains. Harriers were still out. Must have been one hungry bird. It really put on a show for at least 30 min, allowing me to study the Barn Owl body shape and flight + foraging style. Graceful fliers, with a steady wing beat cadence of about 2-3 beats per second and usually fairly deep wing beats, wings held bowed downwards, flying within 5-10 feet off the ground and occasionally twice that height.  Half an hour after sunset, there were at least 3, and maybe 5, Barn Owls hunting.  One bird flew only 10-20 feet above my head, clearly curious: it banked, circled me, and moved on.  One bird called: "hiyaaaaa"

Continuing bird roosting in a silo. First reported on the Michiana Amish Birding Hotline (574) 642-1300 (ext. 4098) earlier this week.  The owl was observed from a respectful distance. The property owner mentioned he has seen two birds – this adult and a fledgling on his property for a number of weeks now. He indicated that the owlet was roosting very close by in an adjacent silo, but we did not investigate further to avoid disturbing the birds.

FRS, submitted 06.13.19  From the list of viewers over 40 people have viewed at least one of these owls in the last two (2) days.  Two Barn Owls, one an adult and an owlet @ 10 inches tall. The adult was perched in the eastern silo and unmoving and had a flat, heart-shaped white face with the dark eyes apparently closed and a dark nose ridge running down towards the beak, the crown was a reddish-brown, with a white breast with some small dark spotting and light brownish-red wings and back also with dark spotting. There was a dark spot in the center of the lower belly which may have been a foot. Closed eyes can be a part of a threat display. The owlet was all white with large dark eyes and a long face and large beak. Possibly wearing it's second downy coat, as the belly had down on it. Evidently Barn Owls are the only owls to get two down coats as owlets, with the first sparse on the belly and with down covering the legs to the claws. The owlet lacked any down on the lower legs and had much down on the belly, so likely it's second down coat. They are said to feather between 3rd and 7th week, fly @ 60 days, and be independent @ 10 weeks.   The adult was perched in the eastern silo, which is @ 175 feet from the western silo which contained silage and was where the owlet was.  The adult had been with the owlet in the filled west silo, but had moved after the daily 4 PM silage removal was performed. The best time to view the adult would be after 4 PM as it flies to the empty eastern silo after silage is removed from the western silo where the owlet is at. According to the property owner the adult will stay in the eastern silo for some time. It was there until 830 PM one night.  Evidently the owlet had hatched @ one month ago as that was when the owlet was first seen. It was found in the western silo which was full of silage and had first been opened up in January.  The owlet was left alone after it was first found until the silage had rotted to a depth of about seven (7) feet and had to be removed. Then it was moved up to the higher part of the silage while the rotten silage was removed.    The owlet was seen today in the western silo. It was at the highest point of the silage and near the wall of the silo. It did not care for company as it was continually hissing for the approximate minute that it was observed. Since there is only one owlet it raises the probability it will be well fed.  Females alone incubates and broods the young, with the male bringing food, but owlets may be tended and fed by both parents.  The average lifespan of a wild Barn Owl is 20.9 months. 60-85 % of Barn Owls die in their first year before breeding. Most birds of 260 birds in one study in Utah, at the northern edge of the Barn Owls range, had only one successful breeding season. Of course successful breeding does not mean these birds were fit as fitness is measured by the successful breeding and rearing of young by the 2nd generation. It doesn't mean an animal is fit if it merely raises young, the young need to be reproductive.    Everything else. https://www.allaboutbirds.org/bird-cams-faq-barn-owl-nest/  https://www.owlresearchinstitute.org/barn-owl   Colder than normal weather and/or increased snow cover increases starvation rate  https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v087n01/p0111-p0115.pdf  https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/dec/14/barn-owls-threatened-freak-weather  PhD Thesis on Sibling Rivraly in the Barn Owl  2nd App shows that darker owlets gave food to their younger siblings and lighter owlets stole food. "before resuming hunting activities the mother and father stay in the nest alongside their offspring for on average 29 and 15 s, respectively"  https://serval.unil.ch/resource/serval:BIB_67DFFDCA1A39.P001/REF

One adult and four older nestlings/fledglings at 2 different DNR barn owl nest box sites. All were seen while performing necessary nest box maintenance (cleaning out and making small repairs to the box when needed). The amount of fresh pellet mass inside the box that had the adult roosting inside the box indicated that there was a nest in the box in 2017. The box with at least four older chicks was not disturbed. These chicks were right on the verge of fledging or had recently fledged and were still roosting inside the box. Small tufts of down were visible in the breasts if these owls. Since this is a dangerous time in the lives of naive young barn owls, we did not want to flush them from their nest box. Another visit will be made in a couple months after chicks have dispersed and the box will be cleaned out then. Nest boxes help barn owls by giving them a safe place to roost and nest. You can help barn owls by donating to the Nongame Fund, or by building and installing a nest box in open grassland habitat. Learn more: http://www.in.gov/dnr/fishwild/3382.htm

Trying to observe or photograph these birds from under the bridge from the Oglethorpe County (south) side of the river, is not needed, would not be responsible, probably would be impossible anyway, or in the best interests of the owl family. Historically known Barn Owl roost site, nesting here not documented previously to my knowledge. Adult Barn Owl seen here in flight on 3/30 from ledge as during prior sightings. Female adult Barn Owl seen here on at least 4/8, 4/10, 4/17, 4/18, and 4/26 incubating eggs (at times thought expired). Owlets first discovered on 5/15. Handheld phonescoped video frame screen captures from the phone in the field.

**very rare on the mainland, approximately annual. While walking along a trail, for an instant a white heart-shaped face started at me from about 10 feet away up in a cedar. I froze immediately, but the bird flushed so I fired off a few rapid shots as it flew away. The back and wings were a mottled blue-gray and orange-buff, and the body was mostly white. The flight was floppy and buoyant. Later I spied the owl perched far off trail among some deciduous trees. I viewed it from a great distance from the trail, and left it there.

Media notes: This is the view when peering inside the nest box via a one inch crack under the unlatched top. The five owlets were about one to two feet away from me. They had not yet left the nest. The fifth owlet is crouching and mostly out of view in this picture. You can see the front owlet is swaying side to side with hunched shoulders, presumably to appear menacing.
Observation Details: 1 adult, 5 owlets. The adult, presumably the mother, was perched near the rafters in the barn. The owlets were in their wooden nest box. Our trip leader told us that he expects them to fledge in about two weeks. At one point a young Amish boy raised the nest box lid and the owlets could be heard hissing and clacking. The image of these beautiful owlets all huddled together, looking back at me with their large black eyes from only a couple foot away, will stay with me the rest of my life! Some pictures are better than none, but they fail to capture the magical experience.

All white with long wings and dark toes. Buffy colored at shoulders and wrist, grey at back and top of tail. Wing span longer than body. Neck ring and perfect heart shaped face. Lifted softly and circled hunting then came around 2 more times before tipping a wing and setting in tall grass.

It was perched facing away from us for about a minute then turned to check us out before flying into Sabal Palm.  We drove by again 10 minutes later and found it near its original perch, this time trying to wrangle some prey out of the tall grasses.  Gorgeous feathers in the setting sun.  There are theories that this species is bioluminescent.

One hunting just after the sun went down behind the mountains. Harriers were still out. Must have been one hungry bird. It really put on a show for at least 30 min, allowing me to study the Barn Owl body shape and flight + foraging style. Graceful fliers, with a steady wing beat cadence of about 2-3 beats per second and usually fairly deep wing beats, wings held bowed downwards, flying within 5-10 feet off the ground and occasionally twice that height.  Half an hour after sunset, there were at least 3, and maybe 5, Barn Owls hunting.  One bird flew only 10-20 feet above my head, clearly curious: it banked, circled me, and moved on.  One bird called: "hiyaaaaa"

Locality: GA-22 South Fork Broad River Bridge (Oglethorpe Co.)
Observation Details: As previously reported there seems now to be only 3 out of 4 owlets, however one of the young birds laid down and I was concerned that there were now only 2, so they can get pretty flat to the ledge and hidden behind the others, but they are getting to be pretty good sized now! Did not see an adult. Request that birdwatchers and photographers not pressure these birds in any way. Trying to observe or photograph these birds from under the bridge from the Oglethorpe County (south) side of the river, is not needed, would not be responsible, probably would be impossible anyway, or in the best interests of the owl family. Historically known Barn Owl roost site, nesting here not documented previously to my knowledge. Adult Barn Owl seen here in flight on 3/30 from ledge as during prior sightings. Female adult Barn Owl seen here on at least 4/8, 4/10, 4/17, 4/18, and 4/26 incubating eggs (at times thought expired). Owlets first discovered on 5/15. Handheld phonescoped video frame screen captures from the phone in the field.

Media notes: The mother owl was perched near the rafters and did not leave this spot while we were present. She seemed to have gotten used to people visiting.
Observation Details: 1 adult, 5 owlets. The adult, presumably the mother, was perched near the rafters in the barn. The owlets were in their wooden nest box. Our trip leader told us that he expects them to fledge in about two weeks. At one point a young Amish boy raised the nest box lid and the owlets could be heard hissing and clacking. The image of these beautiful owlets all huddled together, looking back at me with their large black eyes from only a couple foot away, will stay with me the rest of my life! Some pictures are better than none, but they fail to capture the magical experience.

FRS, submitted 06.13.19  From the list of viewers over 40 people have viewed at least one of these owls in the last two (2) days.  Two Barn Owls, one an adult and an owlet @ 10 inches tall. The adult was perched in the eastern silo and unmoving and had a flat, heart-shaped white face with the dark eyes apparently closed and a dark nose ridge running down towards the beak, the crown was a reddish-brown, with a white breast with some small dark spotting and light brownish-red wings and back also with dark spotting. There was a dark spot in the center of the lower belly which may have been a foot. Closed eyes can be a part of a threat display. The owlet was all white with large dark eyes and a long face and large beak. Possibly wearing it's second downy coat, as the belly had down on it. Evidently Barn Owls are the only owls to get two down coats as owlets, with the first sparse on the belly and with down covering the legs to the claws. The owlet lacked any down on the lower legs and had much down on the belly, so likely it's second down coat. They are said to feather between 3rd and 7th week, fly @ 60 days, and be independent @ 10 weeks.   The adult was perched in the eastern silo, which is @ 175 feet from the western silo which contained silage and was where the owlet was.  The adult had been with the owlet in the filled west silo, but had moved after the daily 4 PM silage removal was performed. The best time to view the adult would be after 4 PM as it flies to the empty eastern silo after silage is removed from the western silo where the owlet is at. According to the property owner the adult will stay in the eastern silo for some time. It was there until 830 PM one night.  Evidently the owlet had hatched @ one month ago as that was when the owlet was first seen. It was found in the western silo which was full of silage and had first been opened up in January.  The owlet was left alone after it was first found until the silage had rotted to a depth of about seven (7) feet and had to be removed. Then it was moved up to the higher part of the silage while the rotten silage was removed.    The owlet was seen today in the western silo. It was at the highest point of the silage and near the wall of the silo. It did not care for company as it was continually hissing for the approximate minute that it was observed. Since there is only one owlet it raises the probability it will be well fed.  Females alone incubates and broods the young, with the male bringing food, but owlets may be tended and fed by both parents.  The average lifespan of a wild Barn Owl is 20.9 months. 60-85 % of Barn Owls die in their first year before breeding. Most birds of 260 birds in one study in Utah, at the northern edge of the Barn Owls range, had only one successful breeding season. Of course successful breeding does not mean these birds were fit as fitness is measured by the successful breeding and rearing of young by the 2nd generation. It doesn't mean an animal is fit if it merely raises young, the young need to be reproductive.    Everything else. https://www.allaboutbirds.org/bird-cams-faq-barn-owl-nest/  https://www.owlresearchinstitute.org/barn-owl   Colder than normal weather and/or increased snow cover increases starvation rate  https://sora.unm.edu/sites/default/files/journals/condor/v087n01/p0111-p0115.pdf  https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/dec/14/barn-owls-threatened-freak-weather  PhD Thesis on Sibling Rivraly in the Barn Owl  2nd App shows that darker owlets gave food to their younger siblings and lighter owlets stole food. "before resuming hunting activities the mother and father stay in the nest alongside their offspring for on average 29 and 15 s, respectively"  https://serval.unil.ch/resource/serval:BIB_67DFFDCA1A39.P001/REF

Presumably was killed by Great Horned the previous night or some other time in very recent past. Flew in at about 4:10 over Heron Pond and landed in the tall grass. When I first saw it flying, I yelled, “Short-Eared” to Oliver, but then I realized the color was odd for it. I hurried and got some pics of it perched, and the Barn Owl was revealed. For a while, it used its spread out wings as support to perch on the tall stiff grass, but then it hoped down only leaving its head exposed for views. This made looks more difficult, but you could still identify it was a Barn by its face. We stayed until dark to where we couldn’t see it anymore, and it didn’t fly up again

Observation Details: A male barn owl was perched in a row of scraggly pine trees at a busy intersection of trails adjacent to the parking circle and near the bathrooms. Mesmerized by the bird, and mainly focusing on it's face, I didn't notice when taking photos initially, that the bird was actually trapped by twine that essentially attached it's foot to the branch.   Another birder called Bay Raptor Rescue, and I returned to the bulb with my wife (after she alerted me to the situation) to try to assist with the rescue, bringing an extra ladder and additional tools. The bird was difficult to rescue, but after perhaps several hours of efforts - involving sawing the branch to leave the bird and branch swinging from the twine, then attempting to cut the twine - the bird was freed and placed in a cardboard pet carrier. The bird was taken to the Lindsay Museum, where it will be rehydrated, its wounds assessed and bandaged and any other issues treated.     Thanks to Craig Nikitas of Bay Bird Rescue who did some serious 'McGyvering' - including tying a slip not to a pole to trap the end of the cut branch to prevent the bird flying away with the branch once the twine was cut. He also balanced precariously on a tall ladder, while I stood on a smaller ladder and handed him tools. My wife, Adrienne assisted from the ground. The bird had serious abrasions to it's leg and foot, and we were unsure whether constriction from the string had caused nerve damage or impairment of the foot. I plan to call the Lindsay Museum in a day or two to ask for an update.

21:32 first sighting flying on east meadow, stayed in the area, landed around us on the field sign one time for ~ 20 seconds, took off and kept flying low at the same area until lost sight of it 21:56 when it dove down and presumably caught something. Observed for another 20 mins without sighting.

Watched 4 Barn Owls for over an hour! They were flying between the trees above us before the sun went down, so it was light enough to get great pictures and recordings. We found them after taking a small dirt path that branched off of the paved trail and led into the trees.  We watched them fly over the fields once it got dark for the rest of our outing. There was a Western Wood-Pewee sounding an alarm call that helped us find them. At one point we were able to see all 4 simultaneously, so definitely no counting the same owl twice here.

Locality: Timothy SE--Private Property: Wrye Branch Rd, Clinton US-NC (35.1325,-78.4217)
Observation Details: I thought it was a cat on the field at first. Soaking in the dew on its wings while being mobbed. It then flew to a nearby fence post and then dove into the bushes along the creek, maybe to get the RWBL's young.   Landowner was weary when I was parked on the road (he had followed me around earlier on my way in) but then I explained that I wasn't a soil or water inspector as he thought (though I am trained in geology!). He ended up showing me where its been living for the past six months. It’s full of pellets. Didn’t check the other buildings, though they look good too. He said he hears it at night and it sounds like more than one. Another one has been living for years near 35.091111°N  78.411073°W in a metal barn. Would be nice to verify that one too.

Student volunteers walked into or approached dense thicket of shrubs on the trail to collect trash, then someone yelled "owl". I was immediately struck by a large, white speckled belly, flat face, and orange-brown body flying above me. I hastily reached for my camera, and captured a few images of the bird flying. It then perched in a tree, then flew off after about 2 minutes. Images cropped to hide potential location information. It has been confirmed that it is not an escaped bird from the ornithology center!
